Both output files have been written.

**Headline finding:** Palbociclib is the only treatment with a real PFS effect in this 50,000-patient cohort. It increases PFS by ~+4.98 months in the joint subgroup `er_positive=1 AND her2_positive=0 AND pik3ca_mutation=0 AND ki67_pct≤14` (n=10,828, ~22% of cohort), and ~0 months outside this subgroup. Each subgroup predicate is necessary — PIK3CA mutation, HER2 positivity, ER negativity, or Ki-67>14 each fully abolishes the benefit.

The other five treatments (tamoxifen, trastuzumab, olaparib, sacituzumab govitecan, pembrolizumab) showed no robust subgroup benefit. Olaparib in BRCA+/HR− and pembrolizumab in TNBC+premenopausal+low-Ki-67 had unadjusted positive signals (+0.83 and +0.54 months respectively), but both collapsed to near zero after adjusting for age/ECOG/stage_iv/has_brain_mets/albumin/weight_loss — chance baseline imbalance, not a real treatment effect.

`transcript.json` (25 iterations, 40 hypotheses, 40 analyses) validates against the schema; `analysis_summary.txt` walks through the prognostic main effects, the palbociclib subgroup-discovery cascade, the heterogeneity searches for the other treatments, and the joint multivariable model (R²=0.994).
